A Unified Field Theory of Universal Consciousness: Mathematical Modeling and Advaitic Foundations
1. Introduction: The Foundational Field Hypothesis
In contemporary theoretical physics, the "Foundational Field Hypothesis" necessitates a radical ontological shift: consciousness is not a computational byproduct of neurobiological complexity, but the fundamental, non-dual substrate of the Hilbert space. This report proposes a model where Universal Consciousness is defined as the primary field (\Phi)—the underlying vacuum expectation value (VEV) from which all matter and energy emerge. Moving beyond the classical Samkhya-dualism of Purusha (pure awareness) and Prakriti (matter/nature), this theory aligns with Advaitic non-dualism (Advaita), positing that the field is both the material and efficient cause of the cosmos. By applying the rigors of quantum field theory (QFT) to the ancient Prasthanatrayi, we define a framework where the manifold universe is a conceptual proliferation (prapanca) within a singular, unchanging substrate.
2. The Mathematical Modeling of Universal Consciousness (\Phi)
The modeling of the universe as a singular, intelligent field requires the definition of a universal variable, the Consciousness Field (\Phi).
The Consciousness Field (\Phi): A universal, non-dual field tensor representing pure, self-luminous awareness (caitanya). It is all-pervading and serves as the ontological ground for all physical observables.
The Ground State (\Phi_0): Representing the pre-Big Bang state of absolute stillness, \Phi_0 is the vacuum ground state of the field. It is undifferentiated, possessing zero entropy and no topological defects. This corresponds to the state of "one without a second," where the field is at rest before the emergence of temporal-spatial coordinates.
Operational Levels within the \Phi Field:
Universal Consciousness: The intrinsic, self-luminous (svayam prakāśa) nature of the field. It is the "Witness-consciousness" (saksi) that remains invariant across all field transformations.
Universal Mind: The informational density and vibratory frequency of the field. It represents the state of "representation-only" (vijñapti-mātra), where the potential for complexity is encoded as field fluctuations.
Universal Thought: Non-linear perturbations and topological defects within the field. These are perceived as conceptual multiplicities (prapanca), which appear as separate instances but lack an independent essence (svabhāva).
3. Dynamics of Differentiation and Symmetry Breaking
The transition from the undifferentiated \Phi_0 to the phenomenal universe is governed by the dynamics of symmetry breaking and the scalar potential V(\Phi).
Scalar Potential V(\Phi): This represents the latent potential energy driving the field toward apparent complexity. In this model, the activation of V(\Phi) facilitates Vivarta (unreal manifestation), where the field appears to undergo a transformation (parinama) while its underlying essence remains invariant.
Quantum Fluctuations and Symmetry Breaking: Localized disturbances in the \Phi field generate "experiential centers." When the symmetry of the ground state is broken, the field appears to partition into subjects and objects. These localized fluctuations constitute the Jivatman (individual experiencing self), which is a mere reflection of the singular field in a multitude of apparent forms.
Turiya as the Background State: The ground state \Phi_0 is mapped to Turiya—the "fourth state" that underlies and transcends the fluctuations of waking (jagrat), dreaming (svapna), and deep sleep (suṣupti). It is the state of non-origination (ajativada), where the field is apprehended in its absolute, non-dual purity.
